{
  "text": "Of course, A h = A(a h ) and a 2 h = a 2 (m h ). In the expression (5.3) we used the following notations for the formfactors: (this corresponds to a massive vector with an extra compensating scalar [CITATION_1] ). The divergent part of the one-loop part of the effective action (5.3) is exactly the Eq. (4.18). Concerning the finite part, it is easy to see that the non-localities of the expression (5.3) have two sources. First of all we meet the tree-level non-localities inside each \u03beK, and moreover there are a-dependent and A-dependent non-localities which have the structure similar to the one for the usual massive fields [CITATION_2] . If considering the \u03b2-functions, the first type of the non-localities does not matter, hence one can expect to meet the same result as in the M S-scheme in the high energy regime and the standard decoupling [CITATION_3] at low energies.",
  "correct_citation": {
